==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*witan'' (present tense ''*wait-''), from Indo-European ''*u̯oidh₂e'', originally a perfect form of ''*u̯eid-'' ‘see’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[wita]], Old Saxon [[witan]]/'''wēt''' (Dutch [[weten]]), Old High German [[wizzan]]/'''weiz''' (German [[wissen]]), Old Norse [[vita]]/'''veit''' (Swedish [[veta]], Gothic [[𐍅𐌹𐍄𐌰𐌽]]/'''𐍅𐌰𐌹𐍄'''.  The IE root is also the source of Baltic ''*waid-'' (Lithuanian [[vadinti]]), Slavic ''*vēde-'' (Old Church Slavonic [[вѣдѣти]], Russian [[ведать]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'wɪtan/

===Verb===
'''witan''' (preterite-present: '''wāt''' ‘he knows’, '''wisse'''/'''wiste''' ‘he knew’, ('''ġe''')'''witen''' past participle)
# to be aware of, to [[know]] (something)

